commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-4553 - iSE2 FOTA Support Tool

1. Add aise_target_create.py to create target_package.7z based on source.7z + AISE_blob.bin + AISE version string
Usage:
    python aise_target_create.py source_pacakge.7z AISE_01_00_00_08_20911.zip

2. Modify entrypoint.py, avms_package.py to support AISE only upgrade package flow
Usage:
    # Generate AISE_01_00_00_07_15121 to AISE_01_00_00_08_20911 AISE only fota package for source FW package
    python entrypoint.py source_pacakge.7z target_package.7z --module HL7812 --aise_src_ver AISE_01_00_00_07_15121

    # Generate AISE_0 to AISE_01_00_00_08_20911 AISE only fota package for source FW package
    python entrypoint.py source_pacakge.7z target_package.7z --module HL7812 --aise_src_ver 0

    # Generate "legacy_module" to AISE_01_00_00_08_20911 AISE only fota package for source FW package
    python entrypoint.py source_pacakge.7z target_package.7z --module HL7812 --aise_src_ver legacy

    # Original flow to create delta package without any AISE
    python entrypoint.py source_pacakge.7z target_package.7z --module HL7812

Resloves: ALT1250-4553
Change-Id: Ie8dab70e85b39d386aad9667004ec48cbad23a4a
Signed-off-by: Philip Yeh <pyeh@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: ALT1250-4553 - iSE2 FOTA Support Tool

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-4552 - Support new exe format packed with IBT

1. Support new exe format in _collect_archive_files(), also include
   u-boot-backup.bin and use explicit prefix for AppFW_flash.bin ,
   u-boot.bin , io_par.bin, pmp.bin, mcu.bin for clarity. Previously,
   u-boot-backup.bin is missed in RK3.x.
2. Extract input archive with _extract_input() only once, the output is
   used in _get_sys_header_filename(), _collect_archive_files() and
   _get_package_version() directly. Previously, the tarball is extracted
   in each function repeatedly.
3. Rename exe_path and extract_dir as in_path and archive_dir respectively
4. Show files collected for tarball for diff generation, and
   show files in downloaded diff tarball

Change-Id: I38f74d9b9b3168e0eb8947ca5df996e94d0a2711
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>

sysHeader.bin.alt1250.dh0.bin_unsigned
config_record_alt1250.bin_unsigned

"system_header_alt1250_E0_SB.bin
system_header_backup_alt1250_E0_SB.bin
system_header_dh0_alt1250_E0_SB.bin
u-boot_E0.bin
u-boot-cln_E0.bin
config_record_ALT1250_E0_SB.bin"

Therefore, we don't need to handle the sysHeader file renaming for RK3.2.

commits.commitMessage:
[ALT1250-4033] Add tool to addr2line the swiheap backtrace

parse swiheap dump or swiheap startLog output for backtrace
and get it's addr2line, then prints parsed input back to stdout
in cleaned csv format or save to file

Resolves: ALT1250-4033
Change-Id: I8538ec7ad414ed5402d485e6285f17638a6a5bda
Signed-off-by: Jeffrey Leong <jleong@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [ALT1250-4033] Add tool to addr2line the swiheap backtrace

comments.message: Is this a command or a piece of data to be processed?
it's the address so you can consider it data
It would help readers to understand the code if you could rename the variable as it is not a "command to run".
Done

From the comment and code, I understand this is a timed blocking call. There seems no parallelism: the main process is waiting on the __queue for the result returned from __process. Also, what could cause a timeout and what would happen if a timeout occurs? Do we need to set the timeout long enough to guarantee timeout never occur?

If the swiheap dump processing takes terribly long, would it help to speed up the process 
- by starting multiple __process worker threads
- by adding another __process to receive the result and do the final process

The thread and queue was not for improving speed, it's for a non-blocking wait on reading the stdout stream that may not immediately have something to read ready which was necessary. The receive side is parallelized. There isn't any need to improve speed, the parsing will take something in the range of ~1-2s for the swiheap dump use case.
Understood. It could also be coded without using threading. It works, anyway.
Uploaded patch set 1.

commits.commitMessage:
[ALT1250-3907] Fix streaming for Windows WSL and high CPU utilization in Linux

CLI Stream parsing on Windows WSL
- sys.stdin.read is a blocking read when run in WSL so multithread
CLI parser and input handler

High CPU usage
- sys.stdin.read non-blocking in Linux and hogs CPU so make it periodic
- make CLI parser thread blocking

Resolves: ALT1250-3907
Change-Id: Ifd3fea896b21abd19585890952c75a50bdf61420
Signed-off-by: Jeffrey Leong <jleong@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [ALT1250-3907] Fix streaming for Windows WSL and high CPU utilization in Linux

Resolves: ALT1250-3649
Change-Id: I029450c5f5dd369c445e088205791f2c5c91a36e
Signed-off-by: Jeffrey Leong <jleong@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [ALT1250-3649] Support RK3 sierra sign w/ Azure Keyvault

comments.message: What is the reason for this empty file?
The __init__.py files are required to make Python treat directories containing the file as packages. Translation: it helps with import
This changes the magic number in the system headers.  I wonder how the BootROM is able to handle this?
the magic numbers is just 3FA1 as defined in uboot modem image verification. They must use the other bytes for something else
Shouldn't this be "key"?
the dictionary key is key_md
Should update this error to include the other allowed images.
Done
This format string seems like it should be like it is going to truncate the platform_id down to 4 bytes.
yes
Should there be a CRC here?
apparently doesn't need one in RK2.1.2, nothing checks it since it's not burned
This seems to mean that only the last image that is sets "is_concat_to_syshdr" to true will be concatenated to the system header.  Is this intentional?
probably not intentional but wasn't a issue we've hit yet
Is this an intentional empty file?
yes

If I'm understanding this correctly, much of the functionality in Create_System_Header.py is being deprecated by the functions in image_signing_tool.py.  In that case the functionality needed here should be extracted from Create_System_Header.py so that we would no longer need to import from Create_System_Header.py.

Are you considering that we are keeping both scripts for the sake of keeping 4.X methods the same? 4.X branch calls Create_System_Header.py and 5.X calls image_signing_tool.py. If we were actually migrating 4.X to image_signing_tool.py i get your point.

Whether we use image_signing_tool.py for 4.X or not I assume that 4.X will eventually no longer be produced as we upgrade and fix security issues.  Given, there are a few errors in Create_System_Header.py that are fixed in image_signing_tool.py where the two tools are doing the same things, it seems strange to me to keep an old buggy tool around because we rely on some of the generic functionality in the script.
Done
extra blank line
Done
Does this need to be wrapped around a #SWISTART/SWISTOP comment?
Done
Same comment as above
Done
Here and the few lines below, need to wrap in SWISTART comments?
I don't see ue_lte_2g.fw and pmp_2g.bin in any of the JSON files. Do they need to be added anywhere?
i handle the 2g variant naming from the caller script
Same comment as above
i handle the 2g variant naming from the caller script
We don't need to generate the second public key now?
not unless we use HBSB

allowing tempFS to properly calculate the space where

can result in secureboot modem verification failure

comments.message:
Just for completeness - is there a benefit to setting the image content to 0x00 instead of 0xFF?
I believe erased flash is usually all 0xFF so I can see setting 0x00 does visually show that this is not simply an erased area, but am curious if there are other benefits.
yea besides distinguishing it from 0xFF, it's also possible there's more magic numbers or information written in other addresses so 0x00 seemed good to keep the rest nullified.

commits.commitMessage:
[ALT1250-3580] Sign PUK2 with root key

- signed PUK2 with root key means booting to
bootloader requires valid PUK2, otherwise bricks
- PUK2 is now made concatenated to bootloader sysheader
- Change PUK2 to be only 1 key

Resolves: ALT1250-3580
Change-Id: I4b1966f26520a4d3966f705613be9081a053ca0f
Signed-off-by: Jeffrey Leong <jleong@sierrawireless.com>

Hi Moe, I tested the offline version of the script and there were some lines it was unable to parse. An example of such a line can be generated using the AT+KUDPCFG? command: 

[Nov 19 11:38:45.283] Line number[824] File ptr [0x20b22] param1[0x0] param2[0x0] param3[0]

I think that in this case the parsing fails since param3 is not output in "0x0" format. I have also seen some "param3[0x]" log entries that cause the same problem. These lines seem to be parsed OK when using the online parsing mode.

commits.commitMessage:
Add txtSfpParser to tools

Offline log parser for .txt style SFP log dump files

Note this tool is an adaptation of miniSfpParser and
suffers some of the same known weaknesses:
-can't decode a log line with 3rd parameter == 0x0
-any line which would 'raise NotImplementedError'
 now just prints the encoded line.

Resolves: LE-13726
Change-Id: I153c131a9834701d9c0411264e8f6e5519cb71e9
Signed-off-by: Justin Lane <JLane@sierrawireless.com>

comments.message:
Version format has been changed since 4.3.1.0.  However, 4.3.1.0 has a special version format (HL78XX.4.3.1.0) which has been dropped in 4.3.2.0 (See ALT1250-3431). Starting from 4.3.2.0, the new version format will be HL7800.4.3.2.0. In this case, ">=" and ">" will be the same due to that 4.3.1.0 package version will not be supported by current fix.  

The current fix should be able to generate correct fota package with old version format and new version format except for 4.3.1.0 package.

> 3> redbend job fails and update.ua file is not available
> 4> redbend job timesout
> 5> FW exe file does not exist in From list or To list
> ...... may be more .....

My understanding is that by default Jenkins doesn't actually check the return code of programs it runs, and that failures are determined inside the build script.
If raising an exception causes tasks downstream to fail, I can just wrap all of entrypoint.py inside a try/except block, but that's definitely bad practice, the proper solution should happen on the Jenkins side.
As for timeouts, I currently have the max timeout set to 60 minutes, it seems that web-upg doesn't actually run jobs in parallel so large jobs could still exceed this limit.

I'm hesitant to add a wrapping try except block; throwing exception information away is never a good idea.
The proper solution to this would be to force this specific script to always return 0 during execution as per https://stackoverflow.com/a/25745593, or globally enable the jenkins job to continue on a non-zero return code with https://stackoverflow.com/a/28448336.

> [avms_package][INFO]: Successfuly generated AVMS package AVMS_AELM400.4.2.1.0.20190801.zip

As the warning says, there is no way to determine which particular module a firmware package is for unless it's specifically generated for that module (module name is stored under PACKAGE_NAME in the package_version file).
Doing module detection at all is already an improvement on the current launch_batch.sh method, which will indiscriminately generate packages for HL7800, HL7800-M, and ELM400 (and not HL7802) regardless of the package types supplied.
When the module can't be detected, the binary content of the deltas are the same across all files (I'm just copying the same delta binary into each zip file), only the strings relevant to each module are changed in the .app file.

Patch Set 19:

> Patch Set 13:
> 
> when --module parameter is provided, the NBIOT value (0 or 1) will be set based on --module type (0 for HL7800-M, and 1 for HL7800/HL7802) with ignoring the setting in package_version file

This is incorrect, the nbIOTXX in the delta file name should be dependent only on the presence of ue_lte.fw2 in the archive and/or the presence of "INCLUDE_NB1=true" in package_version.
For HL7800-M specific builds, the ue_lte.fw2 should be a binary filled with 0xFF bytes, and this is indicated by "NB1_STATUS=NB1_stub_16k_0xFF" in package_version.

Using HL78xx exe files to generate a FOTA package for an HL7800-M probably won't work, since those have non stubbed NB1 images, so the resulting package will probably not apply (similar to a D1 corrupted test image).

it seems only three files (AppFW_flash.bin, partmap.bin,sysHeader.bin.alt1250) are included into the tar.bz2 file. Some of files are missing

The following files will be needed in the tar.bz2 file:
AppFW_flash.bin 
partmap.bin  
sysHeader.bin.alt1250 
sysHeader_backup.bin.alt1250  
u-boot.bin 
ue_lte.fw2

If the build is hl7800 build, then ue_lte.fw is needed
if the build is hl7802 build, then ue_lte_2g.fw is needed instead

Also,
if the fw package include sysHeader_modem.bin.alt1250, the tar.bz2 also need to include this sysHeader_modem.bin.alt1250 file

In general:

the tar.bz2 will always include the following files:
AppFW_flash.bin 
partmap.bin  
sysHeader.bin.alt1250 
sysHeader_backup.bin.alt1250  
u-boot.bin 
ue_lte.fw2
sysHeader_modem.bin.alt1250 ( may or may not have)
ue_lte.fw or ue_lte_2g.fw

commits.commitMessage:
Provide Azure KeyVault backend for signingTool

- Imported the R&D key in a new Azure KeyVault called
  legato-kv-test that is widely accessibly
- Updated Create_System_Header.py to split the generic
  part from the signing backend
- Add KV support to:
  - fetch the public keys
  - sign headers
- Information about the key to use are stored in the JSON file
  provided as an input.
- A sample (uboot,modem)_engaz_md.json are provided to use R&D keys from Azure.
- A sample (uboot,modem)_testaz_md.json are provided to use test keys
  from Azure.
- Provide 2 template files (uboot,modem)_tmplaz_md.json that are
  provided as a base for the Jenkins job to update and execute.
- Allow multiple inputs:
  ./Create_System_Header.py -f uboot_engaz_md.json -f modem_engaz_md.json
- uboot_engaz_md.json does not contain a recovery image
- No extra dependency needed for existing use cases (using lazy loading,
  and providing reasonable defaults)

Resolves: ALT1250-3125
Change-Id: I930b2b376104d83a6ed18807d763530d885bc52e
commits.subject: Provide Azure KeyVault backend for signingTool

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-3138 Adding header to Update Agent for signing

FOTA fails in signed images because the Update Agent(UA) is missing
a 12-byte header inside the u-boot.bin image.

Root Cause:
SigningTool needs the UA header to be included in the UA image so
it can be concatenated properly to build the complete u-boot image.
The UA header is generated at the time of building the u-boot.bin
and is not available to the SigningTool script.

Solution:
Generate a ua_header.bin - ua image with header - to be used by the
SigningTool to construct the correct u-boot.bin to sign.

Change-Id: I205d1845ec3205b21c3ce2866e60e663c934a9e4
Resolves: ALT1250-3138
commits.subject: ALT1250-3138 Adding header to Update Agent for signing

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-3123 [PSM] Device halts in Wake Up

Root Cause:
Invalid DH0 jump address in the signed sysHeader.bin.alt1250

Solution:
SystemHeader signing tools has a hardcoded padding to store the
location of the DH0 jump address. Adding additional fields mean
that the padding value calculated needs to be adjusted such that
the DHO address fields are stored at offset 0xC00.

Resolves: ALT1250-3123
Change-Id: Id6ffa0836d814349921fa24e02d49adb321b991b
commits.subject: ALT1250-3123 [PSM] Device halts in Wake Up

commits.commitMessage:
[DJEMBE-12] Provide a base for cross-compiling (for Windows / Linux x86 / Linux ARM)

To build for Linux x86 (default on Linux)
- gcc-multilib + g++-multilib needs to be installed
$ make

To build for Linux x86_64:
$ TARGET_ARCH=linux-x86_64 make

Regarding ARM, I quote https://www.debian.org/ports/arm/index.en.html:
  The ARM EABI (armel) port targets a range of older 32-bit ARM devices, particularly those used in NAS hardware and a variety of *plug computers.

  The newer ARM hard-float (armhf) port supports newer, more powerful 32-bit devices using version 7 of the ARM architecture specification.

  The 64-bit ARM (arm64) port supports the latest 64-bit ARM-powered devices.

To build for Linux armel:
- an ARM toolchain needs to be provided in the PATH, I used https://toolchains.bootlin.com/downloads/releases/toolchains/armv5-eabi/tarballs/armv5-eabi--glibc--stable-2018.11-1.tar.bz2
$ TARGET_ARCH=linux-armel make
sft: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI5 version 1 (GNU/Linux), statically linked, for GNU/Linux 4.1.0, stripped

To build for Linux armhf:
- an ARM toolchain needs to be provided in the PATH, I used https://toolchains.bootlin.com/downloads/releases/toolchains/armv7-eabihf/tarballs/armv7-eabihf--glibc--stable-2018.11-1.tar.bz2
$ TARGET_ARCH=linux-armhf make

To build for Linux arm64:
- an ARM toolchain needs to be provided in the PATH, I used https://toolchains.bootlin.com/downloads/releases/toolchains/aarch64/tarballs/aarch64--glibc--stable-2018.11-1.tar.bz2
$ TARGET_ARCH=linux-arm64 make
sft: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, ARM aarch64, version 1 (GNU/Linux), statically linked, for GNU/Linux 4.1.0, stripped

Still broken:
- windows build from Linux

Resolves: DJEMBE-12
Change-Id: I501279382301d9fc9e8e330c3a62455494ec36ec
commits.subject: [DJEMBE-12] Provide a base for cross-compiling (for Windows / Linux x86 / Linux ARM)

USER-DEFINED FUNCTIONS
       Functions in AWK are defined as follows:

              function name(parameter list) { statements }

       Functions are executed when they are called from within  expressions  in  either
       patterns  or  actions.  Actual parameters supplied in the function call are used
       to instantiate the formal parameters  declared  in  the  function.   Arrays  are
       passed by reference, other variables are passed by value.

       Since  functions were not originally part of the AWK language, the provision for
       local variables is rather clumsy: They are declared as extra parameters  in  the
       parameter list.  The convention is to separate local variables from real parame‐
       ters by extra spaces in the parameter list.  For example:

              function  f(p, q,     a, b)   # a and b are local
